fields.description: It's simply amazing what they're putting into books these days. It's also amazing that I managed to get two of these without knowing it. This gift is identical to Gift 13. I even used the same wrapping paper for both of them!

I would have loved this as a kid or, for that matter, when I was teaching. A parishioner at a former parish knew me well enough to give it to me for a birthday gift one year. I'm trying to downsize, though, and I'm willing to give up one of my favorite kind of toys. (Ages 8 and up.)
Mission impossible? Not necessarily. Practice on this simple version: NFSSZ DISJTUNBT! This book contains a lot of such things.

The human body needs exercise or it can get pretty flabby. I know that from experience! Well, the brain is part of the body. You wouldn't want it to get flabby would you? This gift might help stave off the flabby brain problem.
I don't want to force or pressure you to take this of course, but it was here last year and it reminds me of what was probably my first-ever Science class. Ages 8 and up it says.

Here's a different kind of a brain game -- one for when you want to relax. Unless, of course, these two characters raise philosophical questions too difficult to ponder. Don't worry. You can snap back to reality on a moment's notice.
American Plastic Bricks were never like this! But it's not LEGO either. You can build moving things, but I don't think they move by themselves. They do light up however! Ages 8-14 they say.
Stack 'em up, knock 'em down, roll 'em around. Who knows what contraptions you could build? Comes with a guidebook to give you some ideas but, after that, it's up to your imagination. Ages 7+
Was it a cat I saw? Backwards or forwards, always the same. It could be the most curious thing you've ever seen... or read.
Now this one could be scary, or at least very strange! If you loved the Twilight Zone, or it's sort of crafty tales, you might enjoy reading this and other books by this author.
It's hard telling what you might end up weaving together with this kit, maybe something decorative, maybe even something useful, though you probably wouldn't want to make a hot pad with it!

Here are more than two hundred old familiar stories in their original form... well, almost original, they are translated into English at least. Be careful, though, they have not been sanitized by Disney or anyone else and could even be quite politically incorrect if not out and out grimm.
for you Adventure fans, this is a duplicate of Gift 1that allows you to color your way through some twisty little things.
Yes, even grown-ups can do this. All you need is a pencil and the left side of your brain. The beauty of what results is entirely up to you.
It's a BOLD new world... or is that a BRAVE new world? I suppose you and your family or friends can work that out as you play. It's from the makers of a well-known card game.
Hey! This little guy can fly! I guess a space cadet in the hand is worth two in the bush. Ages 8+ it says.

If you were locked in a room and could only communicate by teletype, would we be able to distinguish you from a computer? Could you solve the enigma of World War II? if so you may be able to solve these outside-the-box variety of puzzles.
"It's the little things that get me!" Have you ever said that? You may need this tough thing to help keep all those little things in line. Maybe even two or three lines.

Speaking of little things, you know how they always like to get into the silliest places? If you don't grasp what I mean, or aren't the kind to stick to it long enough to solve the problem, this gift may be for you.
More exercise for the brain here. These seem a bit easier than some I've seen lately but good old number one still hasn't gotten number one.
Don't get all hung up over still another puzzle book. This one promises to be a pleasant pastime in spite of its grisly context. I got the one on pages 50/51 without having to guess at all!

These, they say, are challenging. You have to connect things one after the other after the other. Get the picture? To make it easier, I suppose, they included five connecting tools in different colors.

Another exercise for the brain. Originally intended for gifted third-graders perhaps you can use them to stave off the onset of Alzheimers.* You've got to be able to add, subtract, multiply and divide but there are no fractions or decimals to worry about.
* Delay of Alzheimer's not guaranteed.
How many weird things to you know? Do you notice anything weird about the spelling of the word weird? Select this gift to expand your knowledge of the weird.
Can you find the winning color: green, white, blue, orange, yellow or red? Rubik's at it again, though I doubt that he really had much to do with this. Two to six players, ages 7 and up.
Stick 'em up! Or stick 'em down! Play it in the car or on the side of the refrigerator. Some people even play it by mail. It's an old game, but still popular.
These things are always good to have around, especially if you sometimes need to go beyond using your fingers and toes. It only has 8 digits, not 20, but for most purposes, that's quite enough.

Imagine a long trip in a car. you're tired of playing the alphabet game, and "I Spy" got boring many many miles ago. Don't just blurt out annoying complaints, put your mouth to work in another way. 3players, ages 10 to adult it says. And you don't really even need a car!

"Fools names and fools faces are often seen in public places." Mom used to say that didn't she? When you select this gift, even if you make the headlines, it won't be all bad. you might even win. It says 2 to 6 players, ages 8 and up but I think it could be fun for anyone who can read.
This gift will... uh... um... I forgot what I was going to say. Maybe I should be in here with the others.
If you're good at pursuing unimportant things then this could be the gift for you. It's the first edition of Gift 32.
These gifts seem to be designed as a solitaire version but I think it could be adapted for group play easily enough. This is the second edition of Gift 31.

It would not be fun to get into one of these but it could be fun to play. I remember Richard Dawson starting it off may years ago but I don't know who the guy on the front of the box is. 3 or more players ages 10 and up.

You've heard of a ship in a bottle? This isn't it. It does, however, have the power to move, just not over the water I don't think. It may even be Roman Catholic since the packaging says something about it being an RC version. The biggest puzzle may be how to get it out of its package.

I haven't actually gotten this one yet but, no matter, it's the only one for an infant and, at the moment anyway, we only have one infant in the family. Perhaps she ought to pick this one, hint, hint!

fields.comment: I do not know what to say.
I do not know what to say.
Why can't I use apostrophes? Well, that time I could. But it wouldn't let me say I don't know what to say. Hmm... it did this time. Is it just a problem in responsive mode?
Can I say can apostrophe t? No, not when I am in responsive mode.
Can I say can't in Google Chrome? Apparently. But Chrome seems to have other problems in displaying a large gap between the description and the first comment.
Here is my first comment on gift 1.
Can I say can't in Microsoft Edge? It seems so.
Can I say can't in Google Chrome? Yes I can.
Can I say can't in Firefox in normal mode? Yes.
Can I say can't in Microsoft Edge in responsive mode? Yes.
Can I say can't in Chrome in responsive mode? Yes.
Can I say can(apostrophe)t in Firefox in Responsive mode? No!
And this is a remark about gift number 5.

fields.memory: I can only vaguely recall Christmas at Grandpa's and all I remember is that is was loud and crowded.

At the moment, my earliest Christmas memory is being at grandpa's, receiving a little toy piano, sitting on a couch with cousin Kathy, who also got a piano. As I recall, we were playing them and she reached over and ripped a page from my music book that came with the piano. I don't remember what happened after that. I find it odd that this scene is what I remember.

I think my earliest Christmas memory was at Grampa's house. I saw a toy gas station there and I just knew it must be mind. I kept waiting and waiting for Grampa to call my name. I even helped him along: "J-I-M-M-Y" in case he didn't know how to spell it.
My Christmas memory is most often the coffee cake, moist and warm that mom somehow produced in the midst of gifts, Mass, etc.
One of my fondest Christmas memories was the time spent every Christmas while I was at home, making dozens of cookies with my mom while we played Christmas music and talked.
I never saw it happen but I remember that Santa Claus came down an old register in the kitchen ceiling. We didn't have a fireplace for him to use.

One year, when I was stationed at New Buffalo, it was looking like it was going to be a brown Christmas -- no snow anywhere, just dead brown grass.  I remember coming out the front doors of the church after Midnight Mass to the most beautiful white fluffy snowflakes!  It was just like a movie!
Waiting upstairs on Christmas morning,  waiting to be called down to use bathroom,  and trying to sneak a peek at tree when it was my turn.
The living room, so dark and mysterious as we came down for early mass.  Dad at the kitchen stove,  Mom's coffee cake and a doll I named Pat.
Doing extra chores to earn money to buy Christmas gifts.

I remember staring out the windows Christmas eve looking for Rudolphs red nose up in the sky. With planes coming and going from the airport we were convinced any red light was Rodolph at the front of Santa's sleigh.
Baby doll clothes made by Mom in secret.
The thing that I remember the most is getting up before the sun to go to Mass.  And no peeking to see if Santa had come.

I received that electric football game that I had been dreaming about. Later that day I was in the bathroom and heard what sounded like the hair clippers. I was so depressed, I thought Dad decided Christmas would be a good day to cut my hair. Instead he had got out the football game, what a reli
I remember examining the Christmas ornaments on Uncle Jim's tree several times throughout the day in the hopes that there was still more candy hidden inside of them.
I remember our first Christmas here. Everything was so pretty with the lights and the snow! My parents drove us around to see all the lights. It was cold but we were still very excited!
I remember Madeline and I, on the day before Christmas, going to the golf course for sledding. I think Pat Gary and maybe the Wiley girls were involved too. We were hoping to make the time go faster.

fields.text: Which of the following Christmas carols is two-hundred years old this year (2018)?
fields.explanation: The hymn was composed by Franz Xaver Gruber in 1818 to lyrics by Joseph Mohr. It was first performed on Christmas Eve 1818.

fields.text: In which year did Hallmark introduce their first Christmas cards?
fields.explanation: The "Hall Brothers" company, which later changed its name to Hallmark, adapted a new format for the cards: "book" style, 4" x 6". The standard before had been a post card.

fields.text: Which of the following states does not grow Christmas trees?
fields.explanation: Actually, all of the states grow Christmas trees.

fields.text: We're not sure when Santa got his flying vehicle, but it was first written about in which of the following years?
fields.explanation: Washington Irving wrote about it first, but he thought Santa used a flying wagon. Later, Clement Moore wrote that it was a sleigh being pulled by reindeer.

fields.text: How old was Brenda Lee when she first recorded "Rockin' Around the Christmas Tree" in 1958?
fields.explanation: "Despite her mature-sounding voice, Lee recorded this song when she was only thirteen years old."

fields.text: In the Gospel of Luke, how many wise men, or magi, are reported to have visited the newborn Christ?
fields.explanation: Luke doesn't tell the story of the Wise Men at all. We learn about them from the Gospel of Matthew.

fields.text: Which country abolished the observance of Christmas from 1640 until 1958? (Were they going for the Grinch award?)
fields.explanation: Church and State were closely linked in Scotland and, after the Reformation, the traditional Christian festival days fell out of favor.

fields.text: Which Christmas gifts given to prisoners of war in Germany during World War II revealed hidden escape routes?
fields.explanation: When the cards were soaked in water they could peel apart to reveal the secret maps.

fields.text: Which Christmas holiday treat was inspired by a well-known old story?
fields.explanation: The witch in Hansel and Gretel lived in a gingerbread house which they were eating before they got into trouble.

fields.text: What traditional Christmas decoration is actually a parasitic plant?
fields.explanation: "Mistletoe species grow on a wide range of host trees, some of which experience side effects including reduced growth, stunting, and loss of distal branches that bear individuals" (Wikipedia)

fields.choice_text: It Came Upon a Midnight Clear
Around 1783 after the first human flight in a hot-air balloon made by the Montgolfier brothers.
1819 when Washington Irving wrote a book to be published on the Feast of St. Nicholas.
1822 when Clement Moore gave his daughters the poem "Twas the Night Before Christmas" as a Christmas Gift.
1903, about the time of the Wright brother's first flight.
He just says "magi" he doesn't say how many.
Chestnuts (whether roasting on an open fire or not)
